{"badges":["TM31","TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"content":["Place milk into mixing bowl and heat <b>10 min\/80°C\/speed 2<b>.","Add vinegar and heat <b>1 min\/90°C\/speed 1<b>. Leave to sit in mixing bowl for 1 minute. The milk will separate into curds and whey.","Line simmering basket with 1 layer of paper towel or a nut milk bag and place over a large bowl. Carefully pour ricotta mixture into lined simmering basket. Set aside to drain for at least 10 minutes and up to 1 hour. Ensure simmering basket is not submerged in liquid and able to drain freely.","Once drained, transfer ricotta into a sealable container, then place into refrigerator until ready to use (see Tips)."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"","content":["1500 g full cream milk","30 g white vinegar"]}],"id":"r72858","imageLink":"https:\/\/4.bp.blogspot.com\/-fxx3q3Os56g\/XZXXzHdvTHI\/AAAAAAAAf4E\/aJwr3FKFSSw54W9XZ-bWR9zd9EBX8NgBgCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_9i946fbvTYJ_QfXw.png","title":"Homemade ricotta","publishedAt":"2014-07-22T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"51 g","fat":"51 g","uom":"per 1 Complete recipe","carbohydrates":"90 g","calories":"4234.5 kJ \/ 1008.2 kcal"},"usefulItems":"paper towel or nut milk bag, sealable container, large bowl, refrigerator","hintsAndTricks":["For a softer ricotta, reduce draining time. For a firmer ricotta, increase draining time.","You can use ricotta in cakes, sweet or savoury tarts, or as a spread on toast with your favourite toppings.","You can store homemade ricotta in the refrigerator for up to 1 week."],"basicInfo":["easy","5m","1h 15m","1 portions"]}